\intbl \ql \b Summary of Evaluator Report\b0 \line The evaluator indicated that Criteria 1\'2C 3\'2C 4\'2C 5 and 7 do not comply with minimum standards while Criteria 2 and 6 are in need of improvement.\line \line The evaluator noted that the submission is fraught with contradictions and inconsistencies. It is evident that a consultant has been used to assist in the application but that this person does not have an understanding of Fashion\'2FClothing and the Fashion\'2FClothing industry.  The overall credit value varies between 172 to 362 from one page to the other. The exit level outcomes are meaningless and not of the requisite level and complexity. The evaluator also noted that the mission statement is not intellectually credible as it contradicts itself \'2C stating that students will learn \'E2\'80\'9Cinternational best practices\'E2\'80\'9D but that \'E2\'80\'9Cstudents come to the academy to learn the Spero Villioti way.\'E2\'80\'9D \line \line An analysis of the programme reveals that all first year modules are on level 5\'2C second year on level 6 and third year on level 7. The programme thus does not meet the requirements of the HEQF. \line \line The evaluator also found the programme design problematic. The programme design does not include modules that would qualify a graduate to enter any other field of employment other that \'E2\'80\'98bespoke fashion designer\'E2\'80\'99 and therefore would not enable vertical nor horizontal articulation to advanced diploma or degree programmes on offer by state higher education institutions.\line \line One of the modules on offer is referred to as \'E2\'80\'9CCapstone A\'2C B and C\'E2\'80\'9D. An internet search revealed that it is an integrated project that is meant for fashion designers and is the intellectual property of Carnegie Mellon University\'2C Pittsburgh\'2C USA. This only serves to confirm that SVC has little in-house pedagogical knowledge. The programme design lacks pedagogical value and is not compliant with a culture of higher education criteria.\line \line Although the institution claims to include Experiential Leaning at NQF level 5 and 6\'2C  it is not included in the list of modules and does not carry any credits. \line \line The evaluator is also of the opinion that the staff members do not meet the requirements of the HEQC. The staff listed include 1 PhD \'28part-time\'29 and 3 staff members who have recognisable qualifications and who are qualified to teach at  NQF level 6. Five of the staff members have a qualification from the SVC which does not meet the requirement of one level higher than the programme being taught.  The Academic Head\'2C QA and Programme and staff development manager is a consultant. HR is out-sourced. One staff member has a pedagogical background but lacks teaching experience. A few staff members have had little or no industry experience.\line \line The assessment is mainly of practical work and no mention is made of oral\'2C written\'2C multi-media\'2C electronic work that is required by the Clothing \'2F fashion industry. The assessment methods are 25\'25 formative\'2C 60\'25 summative Journal and 50\'25 product development with a total of 135\'25 which further demonstrates a lack of pedagogical understanding. The weighting is drastically imbalanced considering the nature of the programme. \line \line The library houses 200 books which is not adequate.  The budget has not made provision for specific resources and infrastructure.\line \line The Directorate supports the recommendation that the programme should not be accredited. \line \line \cell \pard 

